<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="546" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,481,1514]" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,481,506]" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Distinguished from other anthocorid genera by the following combination of characters: rounded, tortoise-shaped body; basic coloration brown to fuscous; shiny dorsal surface with uniformly distributed, wooly, reclining or semi-erect setae; short and widened head; male paramere C- or J-shaped, slender, apically tapered and accompanied by a median, small, slender projection (
<figureCitation box="[745,922,589,614]" captionStart="FIGURES 24 − 28" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1661,1684]" captionTargetBox="[173,1423,212,1623]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[150,1437,193,1640]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 24 − 28. Male (24 − 25, 27 − 28) and female (26) genitalia of Bilia castanea (24), B. burma n. sp. (25 − 26), B. pilosa Yasunaga (from Japan) (27), and Wollastoniella rotunda (28), named on the figures." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258310/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Figs. 24−25, 27</figureCitation>
) that is homologous with ‘flagellum’ in 
<taxonomicName box="[1372,1436,590,613]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" genus="Orius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1372,1436,590,613]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Orius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[159,245,625,650]" captionStart="FIGURE 29 − 35" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1485,1507]" captionTargetBox="[158,1424,204,1450]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,193,1464]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 29 − 35. Schematic lineages shown with male parameres and female copulatory tube (29, 31 – 34) of five representative genera. 29, Kitocoris hahajima Yasunaga (redrawn from Yasunaga 2000). 30, Montandoniola pictipennis (Esaki) (from Ya mada et al., 2010 b). 31, Orius minutus (L.) (from Yasunaga 1997 b). 32, Bilia burma n. sp. 33, Wollastoniella parvicuneis Yasunaga (from Yasunaga 1995). 34, W. rotunda Miyamoto &amp; Yasunaga (from Miyamoto &amp; Yasunaga 1993). 35, Hypothesized intermediate condition between Bilia and Wollastoniella. Scale bars 0.05 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258311/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Fig. 31</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName box="[316,477,625,650]" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera" genus="Wollastoniella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[316,477,625,650]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Wollastoniella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[496,639,625,650]" captionStart="FIGURE 29 − 35" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1485,1507]" captionTargetBox="[158,1424,204,1450]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,193,1464]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 29 − 35. Schematic lineages shown with male parameres and female copulatory tube (29, 31 – 34) of five representative genera. 29, Kitocoris hahajima Yasunaga (redrawn from Yasunaga 2000). 30, Montandoniola pictipennis (Esaki) (from Ya mada et al., 2010 b). 31, Orius minutus (L.) (from Yasunaga 1997 b). 32, Bilia burma n. sp. 33, Wollastoniella parvicuneis Yasunaga (from Yasunaga 1995). 34, W. rotunda Miyamoto &amp; Yasunaga (from Miyamoto &amp; Yasunaga 1993). 35, Hypothesized intermediate condition between Bilia and Wollastoniella. Scale bars 0.05 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258311/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Figs. 33−34</figureCitation>
); female copulatory tube fragile, totally membranous (
<figureCitation box="[1280,1369,625,650]" captionStart="FIGURES 24 − 28" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1661,1684]" captionTargetBox="[173,1423,212,1623]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[150,1437,193,1640]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 24 − 28. Male (24 − 25, 27 − 28) and female (26) genitalia of Bilia castanea (24), B. burma n. sp. (25 − 26), B. pilosa Yasunaga (from Japan) (27), and Wollastoniella rotunda (28), named on the figures." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258310/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
). The immature form has a fuscous, rounded, hemispheric body (
<figureCitation box="[826,896,661,686]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 − 7" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1800,1823]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,301,1778]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[150,1436,301,1779]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 − 7. Bilia burma, habitat, habitus images and a tingid co-occurring in same niche. 1, Adult female (arrowed) of Bilia burma on Ziziphus mauritiana Lam. 2, Bilia burma, female adult. 3, Ditto, male. 4, Ditto, male (left) and female adults (center), with a coccid (right). 5, Ditto, male adult. 6, Ditto, fifth instar nymph. 7, Monosteira sp. (Tingidae). All images taken on Oct 17, 2015." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258306/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). Detailed generic characters were provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Carayon" box="[151,483,697,722]" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" refString="Carayon, J. &amp; Miyamoto, S. (1960) Especes nouvelles ou peu connues du genre Bilia Distant trouvees au Japon et a Formose (Heteroptera, Anthocoridae). Mushi, 33 (4), 19 - 35, tabs. 4 - 5." type="journal article" year="1960">Carayon &amp; Miyamoto (1960)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="546" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,481,1514]" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,733,758]" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known from the Oriental and eastern Palearctic regions; currently recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[1289,1359,733,758]" name="China" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">China</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1371,1431,733,758]" name="India" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">India</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[151,218,770,793]" name="Japan" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Japan</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[229,340,770,794]" name="Myanmar" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Myanmar</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[350,435,769,794]" name="Taiwan" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
, and Russian Far East.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="546" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,481,1514]" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,805,830]" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Discussion.</emphasis>
This genus is closely related to 
<taxonomicName box="[728,889,805,830]" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera" genus="Wollastoniella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[728,889,805,830]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Wollastoniella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from which it may be separated only by the genitalia; the diagnostic features were argued extensively by 
<bibRefCitation author="Carayon" box="[832,1008,841,866]" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" refString="Carayon, J. (1958) Etudes sur les Hemipteres Cimicoidea. I. Position des genres Bilia, Biliola, Bilianella et Wollastoniella dans une tribu nouvelle (Oriini) des Anthocoridae; differences entre ces derniers et les Miridae Isometopinae (Heteroptera). Memoires du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, Serie A, Zoologie, 16 (5), 141 - 172." type="journal article" year="1958">Carayon (1958)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Carayon" box="[1062,1393,841,866]" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" refString="Carayon, J. &amp; Miyamoto, S. (1960) Especes nouvelles ou peu connues du genre Bilia Distant trouvees au Japon et a Formose (Heteroptera, Anthocoridae). Mushi, 33 (4), 19 - 35, tabs. 4 - 5." type="journal article" year="1960">Carayon &amp; Miyamoto (1960)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Bu" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" refString="Bu, W. J. &amp; Zheng, L. Y. (2001) Hemiptera Lasiochilidae Lyctocoridae Anthocoridae. Fauna Sinica Insecta. Vol. 24. Science Press, Beijing, 267 pp." type="book" year="2001">Bu &amp; Zheng (2001)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Carayon" box="[395,573,877,902]" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" refString="Carayon, J. (1958) Etudes sur les Hemipteres Cimicoidea. I. Position des genres Bilia, Biliola, Bilianella et Wollastoniella dans une tribu nouvelle (Oriini) des Anthocoridae; differences entre ces derniers et les Miridae Isometopinae (Heteroptera). Memoires du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, Serie A, Zoologie, 16 (5), 141 - 172." type="journal article" year="1958">Carayon (1958)</bibRefCitation>
suggested the general body shape and puncture pattern on the pronotum as key diagnostic characters; however, these external characters are now found not to be applicable to every species. In addition, the immature forms of 
<taxonomicName box="[578,633,949,974]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" genus="Bilia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[578,633,949,974]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Bilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[698,859,949,974]" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera" genus="Wollastoniella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[698,859,949,974]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Wollastoniella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species exhibit totally similar (or fundamentally identical) shape (cf. 
<figureCitation box="[379,456,985,1010]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 − 7" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1800,1823]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,301,1778]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[150,1436,301,1779]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 − 7. Bilia burma, habitat, habitus images and a tingid co-occurring in same niche. 1, Adult female (arrowed) of Bilia burma on Ziziphus mauritiana Lam. 2, Bilia burma, female adult. 3, Ditto, male. 4, Ditto, male (left) and female adults (center), with a coccid (right). 5, Ditto, male adult. 6, Ditto, fifth instar nymph. 7, Monosteira sp. (Tingidae). All images taken on Oct 17, 2015." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258306/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Figs. 6</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation box="[510,541,986,1010]" captionStart="FIGURES 14 − 19" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1724,1747]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,195,1702]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1435,195,1703]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 14 − 19. Wollastoniella rotunda, habitat (14), habitus images (15 − 17), a leafhopper (18) and a tingid (19) cooccurring in same niche. 14, Wollastoniella rotunda, adult female (arrowed) on Urena lobata L. 15, Ditto, male adult. 16, Ditto, female adult. 17, Ditto, fifth instar nymph. 18, A typhlocybine leafhopper (Delphacidae: Typhlocybinae). 19, Haedus sp. (Tingidae: Tinginae). All images taken on Sep 28, 2015." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258308/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">17</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="546" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,481,1514]" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">
<taxonomicName box="[199,254,1021,1046]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" genus="Bilia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[199,254,1021,1046]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Bilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is posited to be composed of Asian elements, based on the distribution patterns of the nine known species from 
<collectingCountry box="[214,272,1057,1082]" name="India" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">India</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[330,441,1057,1082]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingRegion box="[481,533,1058,1081]" country="Indonesia" name="Jawa Timur" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Java</collectingRegion>
, the Sundaland (
<bibRefCitation author="Carayon" box="[724,887,1058,1082]" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" refString="Carayon, J. (1982) Wollastoniella testudo n. sp., hemiptere Anthocoridae predateur d'un acarien nuisible au theier a Java. Bulletin Zoologisch Museum Universiteit van Amsterdam, 8 (16), 141 - 144." type="journal article" year="1982">Carayon 1982</bibRefCitation>
) and the Pacific Islands (
<bibRefCitation author="Yasunaga" box="[1178,1357,1058,1082]" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" refString="Yasunaga T (2000) Anthocorid bugs of the tribe Oriini (Heteroptera: Anthocoridae) of the Ogasawara (Bonin) Islands, Japan. Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington, 102, 353 - 359." type="journal article" year="2000">Yasunaga 2000</bibRefCitation>
); more than a few undescribed species have also been found in Peninsular 
<collectingCountry box="[944,1050,1093,1118]" name="Malaysia" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1065,1132,1093,1118]" name="Nepal" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Nepal</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1194,1294,1093,1118]" name="Thailand" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Thailand</collectingCountry>
(Yamada &amp; Yasunaga, unpublished data). In the Oriental Region including the Himalayan area, both 
<taxonomicName box="[1163,1218,1129,1154]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" genus="Bilia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1163,1218,1129,1154]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Bilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1275,1436,1129,1154]" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera" genus="Wollastoniella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1275,1436,1129,1154]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Wollastoniella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are known (
<bibRefCitation author="Bu" box="[285,497,1165,1190]" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" refString="Bu, W. J. &amp; Zheng, L. Y. (2001) Hemiptera Lasiochilidae Lyctocoridae Anthocoridae. Fauna Sinica Insecta. Vol. 24. Science Press, Beijing, 267 pp." type="book" year="2001">Bu &amp; Zheng 2001</bibRefCitation>
). Although the latter genus occurs in Africa (
<bibRefCitation author="Carayon" box="[1009,1173,1165,1190]" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" refString="Carayon, J. (1958) Etudes sur les Hemipteres Cimicoidea. I. Position des genres Bilia, Biliola, Bilianella et Wollastoniella dans une tribu nouvelle (Oriini) des Anthocoridae; differences entre ces derniers et les Miridae Isometopinae (Heteroptera). Memoires du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, Serie A, Zoologie, 16 (5), 141 - 172." type="journal article" year="1958">Carayon 1958</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ghauri" box="[1186,1330,1165,1190]" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" refString="Ghauri, M. S. K. (1987) A new species of Wollastoniella Reuter from Kenya, with a brief note on W. gatti Ghauri (Insecta, Heteroptera, Anthocoridae). Reichenbachia, 25, 33 - 37." type="journal article" year="1987">Ghauri 1987</bibRefCitation>
), the two genera are most probably derived from a lineage (cf. 
<figureCitation box="[753,889,1201,1226]" captionStart="FIGURE 29 − 35" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1485,1507]" captionTargetBox="[158,1424,204,1450]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,193,1464]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 29 − 35. Schematic lineages shown with male parameres and female copulatory tube (29, 31 – 34) of five representative genera. 29, Kitocoris hahajima Yasunaga (redrawn from Yasunaga 2000). 30, Montandoniola pictipennis (Esaki) (from Ya mada et al., 2010 b). 31, Orius minutus (L.) (from Yasunaga 1997 b). 32, Bilia burma n. sp. 33, Wollastoniella parvicuneis Yasunaga (from Yasunaga 1995). 34, W. rotunda Miyamoto &amp; Yasunaga (from Miyamoto &amp; Yasunaga 1993). 35, Hypothesized intermediate condition between Bilia and Wollastoniella. Scale bars 0.05 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258311/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Figs. 32–34</figureCitation>
, B) once present in the Himalayan region where many Asian organisms are assumed to have originated. To demonstrate this hypothesis, however, further broader surveys on the characters are required, which is beyond the scope of this work.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,481,1514]" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">
Members of the genus appear to be predaceous as evidenced by 
<taxonomicName box="[960,1060,1309,1334]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" genus="Bilia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="esakii">
<emphasis box="[960,1060,1309,1334]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">B. esakii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1123,1256,1310,1333]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" genus="Bilia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="japonica">
<emphasis box="[1123,1256,1310,1333]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">B. japonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that have been observed preying on typhlocybine leafhoppers and/or psyllids (
<bibRefCitation author="Yasunaga" box="[858,1035,1346,1370]" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" refString="Yasunaga, T. (2001) Family Anthocoridae Fieber, 1836, flower bugs, minute pirate bugs. In: Yasunaga, T., Takai, M. &amp; Kawasawa, T. (Eds.), A field guide to Japanese Bugs II - Terrestrial Heteropterans. Zenkoku Noson Kyoiku Kyokai, Tokyo, pp. 278 - 303, pls. 85 - 89." type="book chapter" year="2001">Yasunaga 2001</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Carayon" box="[1055,1384,1345,1370]" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" refString="Carayon, J. &amp; Miyamoto, S. (1960) Especes nouvelles ou peu connues du genre Bilia Distant trouvees au Japon et a Formose (Heteroptera, Anthocoridae). Mushi, 33 (4), 19 - 35, tabs. 4 - 5." type="journal article" year="1960">Carayon &amp; Miyamoto (1960)</bibRefCitation>
also documented that 
<taxonomicName box="[353,487,1382,1405]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" genus="Bilia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="japonica">
<emphasis box="[353,487,1382,1405]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">B. japonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
preyed on the eggs and nymphs of cicadellid leafhoppers, and 
<taxonomicName box="[1245,1381,1382,1405]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" genus="Bilia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="castanea">
<emphasis box="[1245,1381,1382,1405]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">B. castanea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was reported as a natural enemy of 
<emphasis box="[530,722,1417,1442]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Lipaphis erysimi</emphasis>
(Kaltenbach, 1843) (Aphididae) which is injurious to black mustard, 
<taxonomicName box="[256,423,1454,1477]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" genus="Brassica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigra">
<emphasis box="[256,423,1454,1477]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Brassica nigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. (Brassicaceae) (
<bibRefCitation author="Ghosh" box="[642,849,1453,1478]" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" refString="Ghosh, D., Poddar, S. &amp; Raychaudhuri, D. N. (1981) Natural enemy complex of Aphis craccivora Koch and Lipaphis erysimi (Kalt.) in and around Calcutta, West Bengal. Science and Culture, 47 (2), 58 - 60." type="journal article" year="1981">
Ghosh 
<emphasis box="[724,782,1453,1478]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">et al.</emphasis>
1981
</bibRefCitation>
). These observations suggest that 
<taxonomicName box="[1236,1290,1453,1478]" class="Insecta" family="Anthocoridae" genus="Bilia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1236,1290,1453,1478]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Bilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species may prefer hemipterous insects rather than thrips which are generally preferred by 
<taxonomicName box="[1024,1184,1489,1514]" class="Insecta" family="Hemiptera" genus="Wollastoniella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1024,1184,1489,1514]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="546">Wollastoniella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species.
</paragraph>
